First heard making a song that was (similar to the song of a brown thrasher from we had heard and seen in Aurora Park in Mission Viejo,CA near where we live) originating from a shrub just behind a tree near the trail. This trail section was near the side water channel full of reeds that has a bridge over it that feeds into the main wash. We moved very slowly to the left of the tree/shrub on the trail to get a better look inside the shrub with no luck at spotting the bird. Then we came back to the right side of the tree/shrub on the trail and briefly saw the bird with our binoculars from a good profile view. It was a smaller size thrasher (compared to the much bigger crissal thrashers we saw earlier) with a small barely curved bill, Grayish brown above with distinct dark streaking across the chest. The bird was visible for only a few seconds before it disappeared from our view deeper into the thrush and was not heard or seen from again. Very shy bird.

Visibility from road great--Overall notes/how to bird:-This region looks awesome. There is no individual mother of all ranches/traps, but a series of ranches on the N side of the region (vicinity of 11th st) look very good. The best strategy is probably to focus on this region on the N end of the Valley. In Fall it would likely take about 4-5 hours to cover these spots well, in spring perhaps just 2-3.

Data based on trip report posted to NVBIRDS, with notes as follow:--The best access to the block is by way of Fort Bidwell, California, by way of the Fee Reservoir road and a very rocky track that proceeds from  there.  Habitat types include rocky sagebrush scrub/steppe, juniper  woodland, rimrock, and a well-watered, lush grassy meadow at the north  end of the lake.  One of our aims was to relocate and confirm breeding  for the Bobolink that Paul Adamus and Kit Larson found there in late May, but we didn't succeed.  However, we only had time to cover a small  fraction of the meadow area, as most of the 4 hours we spent there was consumed by the hike in plus a wide loop we made to give due respect to a bull at the north end of the meadow.
